Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
This creates an interactive graphic that renders as a line plot. It may look like an image, but it's not--it's a symbolic expression that can be manipulated, styled, and transformed.

Have a look at 3D graphics:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
This creates an interactive graphic that renders as a line plot. It may look like an image, but it's not--it's a symbolic expression that can be manipulated, styled, and transformed.

Have a look at 3D graphics:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Graphics3D[Sphere[], ImageSize->200]

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
(*VB[*)(Graphics3D[Sphere[{0, 0, 0}], ImageSize -> 200])(*,*)(*"1:eJxTTMoPSmNkYGAoZgESHvk5KWlMIB4XkHAvSizIyEwuNnaBqGADEsEFGalFqWnMMB0+mcUlmUCaAUFADABJBpXmpBZzAhmeuYnpqcGZVamZJ4A8ABbgFtc="*)(*]VB*)

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
This creates an interactive 3D sphere that you can rotate, zoom, and manipulate in real-time. The output is not a static image but a live 3D graphic object.

It\[CloseCurlyQuote]s all about interpretation.

Let's replace our 3D object with Cuboid inline:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
This creates an interactive 3D sphere that you can rotate, zoom, and manipulate in real-time. The output is not a static image but a live 3D graphic object.

It\[CloseCurlyQuote]s all about interpretation.

Let's replace our 3D object with Cuboid inline:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
(*VB[*)(Graphics3D[Sphere[{0, 0, 0}], ImageSize -> 200])(*,*)(*"1:eJxTTMoPSmNkYGAoZgESHvk5KWlMIB4XkHAvSizIyEwuNnaBqGADEsEFGalFqWnMMB0+mcUlmUCaAUFADABJBpXmpBZzAhmeuYnpqcGZVamZJ4A8ABbgFtc="*)(*]VB*)/. {Sphere -> Cuboid}

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
(*VB[*)(Graphics3D[Cuboid[{0, 0, 0}], ImageSize -> 200])(*,*)(*"1:eJxTTMoPSmNkYGAoZgESHvk5KWlMIB4XkHAvSizIyEwuNnaBqGADEs6lSfmZKWnMMB0+mcUlmUCaAUFADABJBpXmpBZzAhmeuYnpqcGZVamZJ4A8ABJuFsY="*)(*]VB*)

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Props:
  Hidden: true
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
.md
Nothing stops us from taking the same primitives and use them in actual calculations:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Display: markdown
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Nothing stops us from taking the same primitives and use them in actual calculations:

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Input
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Cuboid[{a,b,c}] // Volume 
Sphere[{a,b,c}, R] // Area

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
1

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
Type: Output
%-------------------------------------------------------------------------%
4 \[Pi] ((*SpB[*)Power[R(*|*),(*|*)2](*]SpB*))

